{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὅμως</b>, <br /> <i>conjunction</i> (from ὁμῶς, with changed accent), <b>all the same, nevertheless,</b> used to limit whole clauses, once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (unless it is read in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.565), Σαρπήδοντι δ᾽ ἄχος γένετο.., ὅ. δ᾽ οὐ λήθετο χάρμης 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.393; ὅ. πιθοῦ μοι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1064, compare “Ant.” 519 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κοὐκ ἐπίδηλος ὅ. and <b>yet</b> not so as to be observed, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 442; νῦν δὲ ὅ. θαρρῶ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 193e, etc.: frequently strengthened by other words, ἀλλ᾽ ὅ.\">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>] but <b>still,</b> but <b>for all that,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.85, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 1085, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὅ. μήν (<i>Doric dialect</i> μάν) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 2.82, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 297d; ὅ. μέντοι [prev. author] “Cri.” 54d; ὅ. γε μήν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 631, 822; ὅ. γε μέντοι [prev. author] “V.” 1344, “Ra.” 61: used elliptically, πάντως μὲν οἴσεις οὐδὲν ὑγιές, ἀλλ᾽ ὅ. (i.e. οἰστέον) [prev. author] “Ach.” 956, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 843, “Ba.” 1027 (probably). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> frequently in apodosi after καὶ εἰ (κεἰ) or καὶ ἐάν (κἄν), κεἰ τὸ μηδὲν ἐξερῶ, φράσω δ᾽ ὅ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 234, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 933; but ὅ., though it belongs in sense to the apodosis, is frequently closely attached to the protasis, μέμνησ᾽ Ὀρέστου, κεἰ θυραῖός ἐσθ᾽ ὅ., i.e. κεἰ θ. ἐστι, ὅμως μέμνησο, [prev. work] 115 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; λέξον.., κεἰ στένεις ὅ., i.e. κεἰ στένεις, ὅ. λέξον, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Pers.” 295; κἂν ἄποπτος ᾖς ὅ., φώνημ᾽ ἀκούω 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 15 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: sometimes it even stands in the protasis, ἐρημία με, κεἰ δίκαι᾽ ὅ. λέγω, σμικρὸν τίθησι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OC” 957; ἐγὼ μὲν εἴην, κεἰ πέφυχ᾽ ὅ. λάτρις, ἐν τοῖσι γενναίοισιν ἠριθμημένος 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 728. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> the protasis is frequently replaced by a <i>participle</i>, ὕστεροι ἀπικόμενοι ἱμείροντο ὅ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.120 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κλῦθί μου νοσῶν ὅ. (i. e. εἰ νοσεῖς ὅ. κλῦθι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1115: strengthened, πιθοῦ, καίπερ οὐ στέργων ὅ. 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 712; ἱκνοῦμαι, καὶ γυνή περ οὖσ᾽ ὅ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 680; τάδ᾽ ἔρδω, καὶ τύραννος ὢν ὅ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 851; ἐρήσομαι δέ, καὶ κακῶς πάσχουσ᾽ ὅ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 280: sometimes it precedes, τόλμα.., ὅ. ἄτλητα πεπονθώς, for καίπερ πεπονθώς, ὅ. τόλμα, 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 1029: in Prose, οἱ δὲ.. ὅ. ταῦτα πυνθανόμενοι ἀρρώδεον 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.74; οἱ τετρακόσιοι.. ὅ. καὶ τεθορυβημένοι ξυνελέγοντο 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.93, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.63, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.2.21: exceptionally, ἡ ἰσομοιρία τῶν κακῶν, ἔχουσά τινα ὅμως.. κούφισιν, οὐδ᾽ ὧς ῥᾳδία ἐδοξάζετο 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.75. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> where the protasis does not contain a verb, ἀπάλαμόν περ ὅ. (variant{ὁμῶς}) ἐπὶ ἔργον ἐγείρει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 20; βαρέα δ᾽ οὖν ὅ. φράσον 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 810; κόλακι, δεινῷ θηρίῳ, ὅ. ἐπέμειξεν ἡ φύσις ἡδονήν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 240b. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> used to break off a speech, <b>however..,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 74 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; to refer to something previously said or to the general situation, <b>after all, in spite of all,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.105, 3.28, 80, 7.1. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3676","accentedUnicode":"ὅμως","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G3674","matchingForm":"ὁμοῦ","stepTransliteration":"homou","gloss":"together","_zh_tw_Gloss":"一處, 聚集, 同","_es_Gloss":"juntos","_zh_Gloss":"一处, 聚集, 同"}],"shortDef":"just as; at the same time","mediumDef":"just as; at the same time <br /><b>yet, nevertheless;</b>, with <greek>μέντοι</greek>, <b>but nevertheless, but for all that,</b> <ref='Jhn.12.42'>Jn. 12:42</ref>; <b>even, though it be but,</b> <ref='1Co.14.7'>1Cor. 14:7;</ref> <ref='Gal.3.15'>Gal. 3:15</ref>*","stepGloss":"just as","stepTransliteration":"homōs","count":3,"_es_Definition":"adv. aun ; sin embargo","_zh_tw_Definition":"儘管如此, 仍然, 還是 (約 12:42; 林前 14:7; 加 3:15)","_zh_Definition":"尽管如此, 仍然, 还是 (约 12:42; 林前 14:7; 加 3:15)","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"dầu vậy; dù sao; tuy nhiên, một lần nữa","_zh_tw_Gloss":"雖然","_es_Gloss":"así como","_zh_Gloss":"虽然"}]}